    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, the \"trap\" part makes me nervous. It feels like they've written this so they can just point the finger at me for anything that goes wrong. Are there usually things hidden in these clauses that people miss? Like, are there specific words I should be looking out for that make this even riskier?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right to be nervous; these clauses can feel as broad and unpredictable as a swarm of angry hornets, or perhaps a particularly aggressive band of low-level goblins who just want to steal your shiny trinkets. You need to look for the specific words that give the Disclosing Party the biggest reach, the ones that let them claim *everything*.\n\nThe biggest red flags here are the phrases like \"any and all losses, damages, liabilities, deficiencies, claims, actions, judgments, settlements, interest, awards, penalties, fines, costs, or expenses of whatever kind.\" See how they list *everything*? That's the legal equivalent of a giant, gaping maw ready to swallow your entire bank account. If you see \"any and all,\" it means they are trying to cover every conceivable disaster, from a spilled cup of lukewarm tea to a catastrophic global event, all tied back to your actions.\n\nAnother word to watch out for is \"arising out of or occurring in connection with.\" This is a massive net, and it casts a very wide shadow. It doesn't just mean \"because of a direct breach\"; it means anything that is even loosely related to the agreement. It's like if a",
      "source": "target",
